AB  - Most commonly, 'moving beyond' National Socialism bespeaks a cris de coeur, a wish among some Germans to rid themselves of the moral, political, and financial obligations attending historical memory. While some academics might share in this desire, worrying about Nazism, its place in German history, and the state of the field clearly has a scholarly purpose. Race is a second organizing concept. This theme has hardly been ignored in the field, but it is worth considering how National Socialism both differed from and resembled earlier racial regimes and other twentieth-century political formations. When W. E. B. Du Bois traveled to Nazi Germany in 1936, he brought with him the baggage of prejudice from a country that was shortly to commit itself to a war against Germany in the name of freedom. Ongoing inquiries into Germany's version of the colonial project, or into its relations with Iran, Turkey, Africa, and China, challenge the self-sufficiency of perspectives that approach German history only through the nation-state.
